Function to be used.

lm_eqn <- function(m){
    eq <- substitute(italic(y) == a + b %.% italic(x)*","~~italic(r)^2~"="~r2, 
         list(a = format(unname(coef(m)[1]), digits = 2),
              b = format(unname(coef(m)[2]), digits = 2),
             r2 = format(summary(m)$r.squared, digits = 3)))
    as.character(as.expression(eq));
}

Example 9

p9_data <- data.frame(subejct = 1:8,
                      before = c(126, 131, 129, 122, 130, 131, 128, 134),
                      after = c(131, 121, 131, 114, 133, 119, 127, 129)) %>%
        mutate(change = before - after)

t.test(p9_data$change)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  p9_data$change
## t = 1.4344, df = 7, p-value = 0.1946
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -2.107807  8.607807
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##      3.25
#or
t.test(p9_data$after, p9_data$before, paired = T)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  p9_data$after and p9_data$before
## t = -1.4344, df = 7, p-value = 0.1946
## alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -8.607807  2.107807
## sample estimates:
## mean difference 
##           -3.25

p10_data <- data.frame(subejct = 1:20,
                       group =  c(replicate(10, "low_carb"), replicate(10, "low_fat")),
                      data = c(-10.8, -10.6, 3.5, 10.4, -7.4, -2.6, -6.5, 1.7, -2.9, -7.6,
                               -1.3, -0.9, -1.2, -0.5, -1.6, -0.9, -2.5, -5, -3.4, -1.9)) 

t.test(x = subset(p10_data, p10_data$group == "low_carb")$data, 
       y = subset(p10_data, p10_data$group == "low_fat")$data,
       paired = F,
       var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  subset(p10_data, p10_data$group == "low_carb")$data and subset(p10_data, p10_data$group == "low_fat")$data
## t = -0.62092, df = 9.7417, p-value = 0.5489
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.257914  3.537914
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     -3.28     -1.92

t-test (unpaired, unequal variance)

H0 (null hypothesis): true difference in means is 0, i.e., there is no difference between junior and senior Ha (alternative hypothesis): true difference in means is not equal to 0.

data <- merge(readxl::read_excel("/Users/minsikkim/Dropbox (Personal)/Inha/5_Lectures/Advanced biostatistics/2023F/Midterm_result/BTE3207_2023F_midterm_results.xlsx"),
        readxl::read_excel("/Users/minsikkim/Dropbox (Personal)/Inha/5_Lectures/Advanced biostatistics/2023F/BTE3207_2023F_students_list.xlsx") %>% rename(student_id = "",
       department = "()",
       major = "",
       year = "") %>% select(c("student_id", "department", "major", "year")),
       by = "student_id", all = T
       )
        

t.test(subset(data, data$year == "4") %>% .$total,
       subset(data, data$year == "3") %>% .$total,
       paired = F, var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  subset(data, data$year == "4") %>% .$total and subset(data, data$year == "3") %>% .$total
## t = -0.71597, df = 17.506, p-value = 0.4835
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -10.00839   4.92839
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     37.10     39.64

p-value is 0.48. Therefore, we accect the null hypothesis (there is no significant difference between mean of junior and senior).

Correlation - % score by their orders

midterm <- midterm %>%
        mutate(problem_full_score = case_when(problemset == 1 ~ 6,
                                      problemset == 2 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 3 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 4 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 5 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 6 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 7 ~ 9,
                                      problemset == 8 ~ 5,
                                      problemset == 9 ~ 6,
                                      problemset == 10 ~ 6,
                                      problemset == 11 ~ 9,
                                      problemset == 12 ~ 8,
                                      .default = 0),
               perc_score = score/problem_full_score * 100)


midterm %>% 
        ggplot(aes(x = as.numeric(problemset), y = perc_score, color = as.numeric(problemset))) +
                geom_jitter() +
                theme_classic(base_family = "serif", base_size = 20) +
                viridis::scale_color_viridis() + 
                xlab("Problem set order") +
                ylab("% right answer") #+ 

                #geom_smooth(method = "lm") 

midterm %>% 
        ggplot(aes(x = as.numeric(problemset), y = perc_score, color = as.numeric(problemset))) +
                geom_jitter() +
                theme_classic(base_family = "serif", base_size = 20) +
                viridis::scale_color_viridis() + 
                xlab("Problem set order") +
                ylab("% right answer") + 
                geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
                geom_label(x = 7.5, y = 100,
                  label = lm_eqn(lm(data = midterm,perc_score ~ as.numeric(problemset))),
                  parse = TRUE,
                  family='serif',
                  size = 8, label.size = 0, color = "blue")
